        <p><strong>Where SpyFu wins:</strong> if your job is research, competitive analysis, or running a multi-client agency — SpyFu earns its keep. <strong>Where theStacc wins:</strong> if your job is growing organic traffic without hiring a content team. Pick by the job, not the brand.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is SpyFu?</h2>
        <p>SpyFu is a competitor research platform that reveals the keywords, ads, and rankings any website has used over time. It indexes search results and ad auctions continuously, building a historical database of what domains rank for and what ads they run.</p>

        <p>As of 2026, SpyFu claims <strong>7.2 trillion search results indexed, 13.1 billion keywords with advanced metrics, and 152 million websites tracked</strong>. The signature dataset is PPC ad history — every Google Ads keyword bought, every ad copy variation tested, every estimated monthly ad spend — going back to 2006.</p>

        <p>What SpyFu <em>does not</em> do: it does not write content, publish to a CMS, track technical SEO issues, handle local SEO, or generate social media posts. It is a research and intelligence tool — nothing more. If your workflow ends at 'I now know what my competitor does,' SpyFu is sufficient. If it continues to 'I now publish content that outranks them,' you need more tools and people.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Company background</div>
          <p>2005, founded by <strong>Mike Roberts in Scottsdale, Arizona</strong>. Originally launched as 'GoogSpy' before rebranding to SpyFu in 2006. Bootstrapped — no venture capital, no parent company. Roberts still runs it as CEO with a team of roughly 21–50 people. That independence shows in the product: focused, opinionated, and priced aggressively low.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="features">SpyFu features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>
        <p>The feature surface is broad. Here is what actually matters in daily use, broken down by module.</p>

        <h3>1. Competitor PPC Research</h3>
        <p>SpyFu's signature feature. Every Google Ads keyword a domain has bought, every ad copy variation tested, and estimated monthly ad spend — <strong>going back to 2006</strong>. Semrush and Ahrefs show current ads. SpyFu shows the full history.</p>

        <h3>2. Ad Copy Database</h3>
        <p>Includes negative keyword suggestions — keywords competitors are actively excluding from campaigns. Tactical gold for PPC managers. The ability to see which headlines a competitor abandoned (and which they kept) saves real budget.</p>

        <h3>3. SEO Competitor Research</h3>
        <p>Keywords any domain ranks for, top-ranking pages, and historical ranking position changes. Less fresh than Ahrefs (data is monthly-updated for most domains) but adequate for monthly competitive snapshots.</p>

        <h3>4. Kombat (3-way comparison)</h3>
        <p>Visual Venn diagram showing keyword overlap between you and two competitors. Identifies the 'gap' keywords competitors rank for that you do not — and the 'opportunity' keywords none of you target yet.</p>

        <h3>5. Backlink Builder</h3>
        <p>Identifies competitor backlinks and surfaces likely link prospects via email + outreach templates. Less polished than Ahrefs but workable.</p>

        <h3>6. Sales Leads</h3>
        <p>Contact information for marketing decision-makers at domains you research. Useful for agencies prospecting new accounts.</p>

        <h3>7. What is missing</h3>
        <p>No technical site audits, no content optimisation scoring, no local SEO, no social media tools, no AI writing, no auto-publishing. SpyFu is intentionally a focused competitor-intel tool — not an all-in-one platform.</p>

        <h2 id="pricing">SpyFu pricing — what it really costs in 2026</h2>
        <p>SpyFu publishes pricing. Most reviews quote the sticker. We will quote the <em>full</em> cost — sticker plus everything you have to bolt on to actually publish content.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Plan</th><th>Monthly</th><th>Annual / mo</th><th>What you get</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
